 to describe any kind of artificial written norm but sets out to capture a range of different kinds of ways that Ni-Vanuatu will say things in various contexts, both written and spoken, formal and informal. The thrust of this volume is to show that Bislama has a grammar—an unfamiliar concept for those educated in Vanuatu. It also shows that Bislama is a language of considerable complexity, which will come as a surprise to many of its users, who have been taught to view their language as somehow "simple" and even "deficient."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 0aBislama languagexGrammar. 7aFOREIGN LANGUAGE STUDY / Oceanic & Australian Languages.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHawaii eBook Package 2000-2013z978311056414340uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978082485007440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780824850074423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780824850074.jpg  a978-3-11-056414-3  Hawaii eBook Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles